sec.p:
A total of 34 students in a social psychology class at a Midwestern university received a list of 13 commonly used expressions that reflect ethnic or national stereotypes (see Table 1
). The stereotypes embedded in these phrases were verified by the American Heritage Dictionary and the Morris Dictionary of Word and Phrase Origins (Morris & Morris, 1988). Students reported whether they had personally used the expression (yes or no) and rated the perceived valence of each expression using a 5-point scale (1 = positive, 5 = negative). Next, students met in groups to discuss their definitions, when and why the terms were used, and their evaluation of those terms. After the discussion, students answered the free-response question, “What are the major goals of the exercise?” and used a 5-point scale (1 = strongly agree, 5 = strongly disagree) to answer three closed-ended questions about the exercise (see Table 2
).
